title: For Sale/Trade:  Finnish M28 Mosin Nagant...
postcontent:
Just the facts...

- Non matching numbers on mag plate, receiver, and bolt handle...typical finnish
- SY stamped on top of barrel=Produced by Sig, type 2 barrel, civil guard abbreviation
- S69246 crossed out on right side of receiver=Sortavala district
- As far as I can see, no 'D' stamped on barrel=never modified to 7.62x54R, assuming 
  still 7.62x53R
- No double sling slots on stock
- Only has Finland stamped on end of barrel, right side, no importer information=
  Pre 1969 Import?
- Though not the same model, look what Simo Hayha did with one...

Going to post pics ASAP, trying to get a decent one with crappy phone camera.
Included is book that explains most of the gibberish above...

If you are still reading and can make sense of it, this may be the rifle for your collection!
I have never fired it, only admired it...

title: For Sale/Trade:  FN Browning Hi-Power (Sale Pending)
postcontent:
Israeli police trade in Browning Hi-Power. This gun was manufactured by FN in Belgium. Shows signs of wear but nothing too dramatic considering its history. 

For those that don't know This was the last weapon designed by firearms genius John Moses Browning, and finished by FN engineer Dieudonne Saive, the Hi-Power was built in response to a French Army requirement for a simple, rugged, 9mm pistol. It has become one of the world's most proliferated handgun, serving on both sides of the Second World War. Eventually finding its way into the arsenals of Great Britain, Canada, Australia, Israel, Lebanon, Syria, Iraq, Libya, Argentina, etc and is still common among the world's military and police forces.

Great shooter and very accurate as well as an amazing piece of history. Please message with any other questions.
